From d779299e16aa48f5618211d126cc0149636d7150 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Alexandre Cordeiro <alexandre.s.b.cordeiro@gmail.com>
Date: Thu, 21 May 2026 08:19:23 -0300
Subject: [PATCH] Recover from MLX Metal command-buffer errors without failing
 the whole batch step
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

When MLX (with the exception-safety patch for mlx-explore/mlx#2670 applied) surfaces a `[METAL]` Command buffer execution failed at the next eval/finalize/synchronize waitpoint, that waitpoint can be in either of two paths inside oMLX:

1. **Decode path** — inside `BatchGenerator.next_generated()`.
2. **Prefill path** — inside `mx.eval([c.state for c in prompt_cache])` in `_do_external_prefill`. This is the cold-start failure mode observed under multi-model memory pressure (multiple iso oMLX processes loading models simultaneously, where Metal allocator headroom is tight and a long prefill triggers `kIOGPUCommandBufferCallbackErrorOutOfMemory`).

Without recovery the step fails, the engine loop logs an unhandled error, and every pending /v1/* request on the process gets a 500 — the failing request AND every innocent sibling.

Adapt to the v3 contract: catch only the `[METAL]`-prefixed RuntimeError on both paths, isolate the failure to the affected request, finalize it with `finish_reason='error'`, and continue the step.

## Decode-path victim heuristic

mlx-lm does not currently expose per-uid attribution for Metal errors raised inside the BatchGenerator. The decode-path catch marks the most-recently-admitted running request as the victim. Trade-off:

* fail-the-whole-batch loses N - 1 innocent requests per error
* fail-one-victim occasionally blames an innocent late-arrival when the actual culprit was an older sibling

The latter is strictly better when bursty error rates inside a batch are the norm. A future mlx-lm change exposing per-uid Metal attribution would close the heuristic gap; until then, document the behaviour in the operator-visible error message.

## Prefill-path attribution is exact

The prefill catch runs inside `_schedule_waiting`'s per-request loop, after the request has been popped from `self.waiting` and its temp UID assigned. The failing request is unambiguous — no heuristic is required. The catch cleans up the temp UID mapping, removes the prefill-tracker entry, drops the request from `self.requests`, and emits a `RequestOutput` with `finish_reason='error'` into the same `rejected_outputs` list the preflight memory guard already uses.

## Cascade-safe cleanup

The decode-path recovery finalizes the victim before calling `_cleanup_finished([victim_id])`. If that cleanup itself hits a `[METAL]` cascade from `_safe_sync_generation_stream`, the recovery now logs a warning and defers the cleanup to the next step instead of letting the exception escape and kill the engine loop. The victim is already finalized at that point, so the safety goal is preserving the batch and keeping the process alive.

## Observability

`Scheduler._metal_errors_recovered` counts successful recoveries on both paths over the engine lifetime. Each occurrence is logged at warning level with the request id and underlying error string.

## Composition

* Pairs with mlx-explore/mlx#2670 (exception-safety patch). Without that patch in MLX, Metal errors abort the process and neither recovery path is reached.
* Compatible with the recently-landed `--max-completion-batch-size` flag (`feat/max-completion-batch-size`). When batch=1 the decode-path recovery surface is simpler (always fail the lone request); when batch>1 the heuristic above applies. The prefill-path attribution is exact regardless of batch size.

## Tests

`tests/test_metal_error_recovery.py` covers the predicate (`[METAL]` prefix detection) and the counter initialisation. End-to-end scheduler construction needs a model checkpoint; the integration test is documented in the PR description and is the natural follow-up once a fixture lands in the oMLX test harness.
